  "format": "Sean Fennessey and David Shoemaker record a late-night emergency breakdown of Avengers: Infinity War: Thanos as a sympathetic villain, the performances that hold it together, and, after a spoiler warning, the snap, who dies, and the Captain Marvel tease.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "First reactions",
      "note": "spoiler-free",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Avengers: Infinity War",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "A 2-hour-40 culmination of 19 films, watched opening night. Both agree it barely works as a conventional movie but clears an impossibly high bar. Josh Brolin's Thanos is a thoughtful, near-sympathetic villain with a balance-of-the-universe code. They single out Chris Evans, Chris Hemsworth and Tom Holland's Spider-Man, and flag Doctor Strange's quippiness and the crowded IP juggling as strain points."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Spoilers: the snap and what's next",
      "note": "who dies, and the MCU slate ahead",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Captain Marvel",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Teased in the lone stinger: Nick Fury pages her insignia as he dusts. The hosts predict Brie Larson's 1990s-set space hero becomes the key to beating Thanos in Avengers 4, though they wonder whether anyone actually cares about the character yet."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ant-Man and the Wasp",
          "year": 2018,
          "note": "The other tentpole holding up Marvel's year. Sean jokes it's a franchise whose lead didn't even have his own comic for the MCU's first six years."
        },
        {
          "title": "Avengers: Endgame",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Referred to here as the untitled fourth Avengers film, once billed 'Infinity War Part II.' They call the ending a Hunger Games-style cliffhanger and bet most of the dusted heroes return, with a couple kept dead as contracts expire."
        }
      ]
    }
